bc89dc4ac2a04f3aae685f619bb0fd24.prefix:
When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the “Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

I thought that there was a lot of
bc89dc4ac2a04f3aae685f619bb0fd24.infix: hubub on the news, but I didn't know what it was all about until I sat down to really pay attention. "It's a tragedy!"

constraints.suffix:
the newscaster was gasping. "The government has been hiding the side effects of the immortality drug for decades!" I settled into my seat, feeling my knees creak and hearing my joints audibly pop. I winced. I'd always half felt sorry for myself that I was too old for the drug, but the other half of me knew, just knew that the other shoe would drop some day. I sighed and adjusted my pillow behind my aching back as I turned up the volume to listen. My ear weren't what they used to be.

"They're pulling the drug immediately!" the newscaster was almost shrieking, and I could see her panic. "They say the effects of the drug will wear off exactly 58 years after they were first administeded!" I could see the shock and disbelief of her terrifically youthful face. "We're all going to get...old!" She could barely get the word out. Like it was a curse. I felt a twinge of pity for her. Here I'd had my whole like to settle into myself and get used to the aches and pains, to get comfortable with the notion of my own mortality. These younger people who had lived their whole lives feeling immortal They were about to hit a hard reality.

I turned off the TV and settled back into my chair. This would change everything, I realized. There would be repercussions all through society. People who had put off having kids because they had all the time in the world suddenly had no time. There weren't many kids around, I realized. The world could be in for a whole lot of trouble if its whole work force suddenly aged out of their ablilty to work. My dawning sense of dread was only slightly assuaged by the fact that I was too old to really feel the repercussions of this. I'd be dead before it really got bad. I pressed the button on my phone to call the assistant in my home. I loved it here, I mused, as I waited for her to respond. This retirement community was the perfect place to hide out and live my last decade or two in peace. I pushed the button again. And again. Finally I called the front desk. A harried voice answered. 

"Is it an emergency?" the woman squawked at me, "You should call the police if it is. Nobody's coming! Everyone left!" I sat up. "What did you say?" The dread was spreading through me like a nagging fever in my bones. "They left!" She repeated. "They all realized they don't have much time left to be young; nobody wanted to be stuck here for the last good year they have left!"

"But you're still here," I tried to argue, although I heard the wavering in my own voice. 

"I'll be outta here as soon as I find my purse," she said distractedly. "Sorry, pal. You're on your own."

And then I realized that everything was about to change for the worse, and not just for the fools who tried to make themselves young forever.   I was about to be alone. For the rest of my life. However long it would be.

When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the “Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

By then, the world is almost entirely filled with bright-eyed, attractive, youthful young adults. People like
111ee57118054cc6b8fa4ef98c1a3408.infix: you have to hide on the edges of society, avoiding their judgemental gazes at

constraints.suffix:
all costs as you become more and more decrepit and they remain strikingly beautiful.

Because of that, you don't even hear about the breakthrough discovery until weeks after it's become a global sensation. The first time you hear about it, you're in the middle of a crowd of young adults waiting to get into the grocery store.

A girl in front of you in the line spots you and grabs you by the shoulders.

"You're one of the lucky ones," she weeps, nearly knocking you off your feet with her youthful strength. "You're one of the Lost Generations, aren't you?"

It's silly that she needs to ask, because it's obvious. But you nod anyways.

Her tears fall faster. "Please remember me," she sobs, flinging herself into your arms and squeezing your shoulders in a tight embrace. "Remember all of us when we... when we..."

Her words choke to a halt, leaving you baffled and afraid.

A young man approaches you and places his hand on her back. He also looks sad.

"We're sorry," he says to you. "For all the times people like us... well. We didn't know, of course. And we never got the choice, did we? People like us... this is the end of the line, isn't it?"

You don't know what to say. You have no idea what they're talking about. So you nod, hoping it might mean something to them.

Sniffling, the girl detaches from you and takes the young man's hand. "Please remember us," she repeats, giving you one last mournful stare before stepping through the store door.

As the automated door shuts behind her, you realize it's covered in a large poster, marked with the seal of the government. It's a warning about the side effects of the immortality drug.

You read the poster, and the world falls out from under you.

"Due to the violent development of suicidal-homocidal tendencies in adults who have received anti-ageing treatment, we ask that all members of the affected population (ages 26-83) turn themselves in for containment and voluntary destruction. This facility has been marked as a designated internment location. Groceries for youths and members of the Lost Generations can be found down the road at the convention center."

e192ae618004434e80f6d9ac86b84b05.prefix:
When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

Dan woke up early that morning, as usual, had his cup of coffee, like usual, and sat down to watch the morning news, as usual. Everything was as it always was. To be honest, he was beginning to be okay with the fact that he would die someday - it wasn't the bitter disappointment is was almost 60 years ago. 

But then the morning was "as usual" anymore. 

Dan was watching the news when the anchorwoman, a young woman who had been with the station for about a year, suddenly froze. She looked about 22, the age most people got the drug, though some got it as early as 16. She was frozen in place, her eyes wide and her mouth slightly open. Staring at the paper and then the teleprompter in front of her. She finally spoke, voice shaky, "I'm sorry, we have breaking news." Last month the earliest recipients of the drug 4EvR all reported to medical centers complaining of headaches. Within 6 hours they had lost their vision and hearing. Within 24 hours they seemed to be comatose, though brain scans showed the same activity levels as a normal, conscious person. They remain in that state."

Dan stared at the screen in shock. The newscaster continued. "Scientists have been studying

constraints.suffix:
and have come to the conclusion that it is due to the drug 4EvR." She began to cry, "And according to their findings it is not only an inevitable side effect, but also one that is triggered or transmitted to users. To summarize, all people who have ever taken 4EvR will almost certainly have been exposed to others who have been exposed to the original group and we should all expect to experience the same side effects within 2 weeks at the most." 

Dan turned off the TV. He was in shock. He had never taken the drug missing the age cut off by a mere two years, but all of his younger relatives had. His children, his grandchildren, so many others. Ans soon they would essentially be helpless with only a few aged people like himself to take care of them. 

Dan was suddenly filled with rage. It wasn't fair. He had had expectations, and now everything was upside down. This was not his problem to deal with. He sat at his desk, and shaking, wrote notes to all his loved ones. He wrote a note to his children, telling them how much he loved them, and how he was sorry that he couldn't be there to help them. And then he went upstairs, and found the bottle of pills, the same ones his wife had used a few years ago when she just got tired of being old in a young world. And he took many more than needed. And left the world before everyone, just like he always thought he would.

I set out to find ways to make a difference in the world. I have decided to use my time to help the world. Just then, there's a knock at the door. I open the door and there is a man standing there. He tells me that he is here to take me to the government. "I don't have an appointment with the government."

"No," the man says. "You work there now." 

"What?" I ask.

"When you took the drug, you consented to 5 years of service. Didn't you read the form?" 

"I don't remember signing a form."

The man sighs. "You were given a form when you took the drug. Look, I don't have time to get into legal stuff with you. I'm just your driver. We gotta go."

I sighed. Well, I wanted to make a difference. Let's get to work, I thought. I grabbed my coat and followed the man to the car. Once I was buckled in, I asked, "So, what's my job?" 

The man said nothing. He just started the car and drove away.

"I didn't bring a lunch or anything. Will there be a cafeteria there? At work?" I asked.

Again, the man said nothing. 



The man drove for hours. We were in the middle of nowhere. Finally, we arrived at a building. The man led me inside and we walked down a long hallway. He stopped at a door and opened it. When he opened it, I saw a man standing there in a suit. Not just any man. It was the President. "Welcome to the government," he said. "And welcome to your first day at work." 

"What is my job?" I asked.

"This is your job. My job." he said. "You are now the President of the United States."

"Why me?" 

"You're the only one who can do this job. We chose you out of many. We think you are ready. Welcome aboard, Mrs. President."

You also feel slightly envious, given that you never knew your own parents, who died in a car accident when you were two years old. 3d6d562a736a49509c20be372a83d111.prefix:
Humans once wielded formidable magical power. But with over 7 billion of us on the planet now, Mana has spread far too thinly to have any effect. When hostile aliens reduce humanity to a mere fraction, the survivors discover an old power has begun to reawaken once again.

The story begins with a young man named Riku, who lives in a world where magic has long been forgotten. He has been raised in Landro by his grandfather Frezna, a wizard, and has always dreamed of becoming a great wizard himself.  Riku didn't know what had ever happened to his parents; his grandfather refused to tell him.  He lived a lonely, isolated life and longed for a family outside his grandfather.  There were no photographs of his parents; the only picture was of a woman.  Sometimes he would see his grandfather gazing at the photograph, a wistful look on his face.  

His grandfather spent years training him, but it takes a long, long time to learn everything one needs to know to use magic to its full extent.  When Riku was 14, his grandfather passed away.

You're Barack Obama. 4 years into your retirement, you awake to find a letter with no return address on your bedside table. It's a secret code that you heard when you were President. A code that needs to be activated only in cases of the utmost urgency. You quickly call the number, horrified at what you will find out. I'd always half felt sorry for myself that I was too old for the drug, but the other half of me knew, just knew that the other shoe would drop some day. I sighed and adjusted my pillow behind my aching back as I turned up the volume to listen. My ear weren't what they used to be.

"They're pulling the drug immediately!" the newscaster was almost shrieking, and I could see her panic. "They say the effects of the drug will wear off exactly 58 years after they were first administeded!" I could see the shock and disbelief of her terrifically youthful face. "We're all going to get...old!" She could barely get the word out. Like it was a curse. I felt a twinge of pity for her. Here I'd had my whole like to settle into myself and get used to the aches and pains, to get comfortable with the notion of my own mortality. These younger people who had lived their whole lives feeling immortal They were about to hit a hard reality.

I turned off the TV and settled back into my chair. This would change everything, I realized. There would be repercussions all through society.

When you die, you appear in a cinema with a number of other people who look like you. You find out that they are your previous reincarnations, and soon you all begin watching your next life on the big screen. As your next life unfolds, you experience all kinds of emotions. You laugh and cry at so many scenes, you watch them go by with no accounting for time. You have no idea how much time is passing. You can't feel it and there is no timekeeping mechanism on display, anywhere in the theater. You are just watching your next life, and you are watching it unfold in real time.

It feels so odd to watch day turn to night, and months pass, on screen. You don't feel bored and you have no concept of time passing, in your space. You wonder how all of this is possible? How can you be watching your next life, in real time, and how can you be watching it in a theater, with other people who look just like you? These questions are huge. You decide to ask one of the other audience members, a woman sitting right next to you. She shrugs her shoulders and speaks, but you don't understand

constraints.suffix:
language. You return the shrug, but don't bother speaking. 

You look back at the screen, and you see your next life unfold. You see every mistake that you make in your next life. You want so badly to tell your next self not to make so many mistakes, but you are powerless to do so. You don't understand the point of this exercise. You feel like you are watching a movie, and you are powerless to change the outcome. This all seems like some kind of sick joke.

You look around the theater and wonder if some of them may speak English, your native tongue (at least in the life that you lived). It's impossible to tell. They all look just like you, men and women alike. You wonder if they are your previous reincarnations, and you wonder how many of them are watching their next life, in this theater.

You know that you are connected to these other beings, by appearance alone, but you don't understand the point of being here with them, if you can't communicate to them. You don't understand why you are watching this film of your next life, if you are powerless to intervene. You want to ask someone, but you don't know who to ask. The questions begin to form in your mind, you have specific ideas on how to improve things but can't say them in a language that your fellow audience members will understand. Suddenly, you have a very specific question on the tip of your mind. You notice that others are looking at you, and suddenly you realize that they can communicate with you telepathically. They are offering suggestions and ideas, based on your concentrated thought. 

You ask your question, and they answer. You begin to realize that the person on the screen is another incarnation of all of you. When one of you asks a pointed question, and everyone else answers, somehow the person on the screen gets the same thoughts. Now it makes sense. You are all connected, and you are all watching your next life unfold, in real time.  This is the evolution of your being and you finally understand life, and death.

Humans are now discovering that they have the power to travel back in time.  This has become true for one man in particular, Bob.  Bob didn't realize he had this power until the day that he lost his favorite sunglasses.  But when he slips back to the day where he first found them, something unexpected happens.  He couldn't figure out how to come back to the present time.  Traveling through time was such a new power for humans that he didn't know what to do.  He sat on a nearby bench after

"Do you have any idea what time it

constraints.suffix:
is?" he asked a passerby.
"It is time for you to go home," she replied.
Bob was confused. He wanted to get home.  But just then, a though popped into his head.  Maybe, just maybe, that was a clue for him to be able to find his way back to the present time.  Maybe he had to find his home.  And he was closest to his home at the time. So off he went for the short walk to his house in the small neighborhood just outside of the city.

Coming back to his house, Bob was confused as to why he was supposed to come here. Everything looked the same and he didn't know what to do to get back to the present time.  All Bob wanted to do was get his sunglasses and it has turned into a daylong adventure!  

Bob began to walk from room to room in his house to search for a clue on how to get back to the present time. As he walked through the kitchen, he noticed a strange looking plant.  Bob didn't own any plants so he thought it was odd that it was there.  It was the only thing out of place.  

"I don't know why but I think that plant has something to do with me getting back to the present time," Bob thought. He began to inspect the plant further.  It seemed to have some sort of small berries on it.  They were purple, looked plump and round, and smelled delicious.  Bob was so curious about the plant that he decided to pick one of the berries and take a bite.

Bob started to feel very tired within seconds of ingesting the mysterious berry.  He was now regretting this decision.  He collapsed on the kitchen floor.  He was unable to do anything as he drifted off into an odd dream. When he awoke, he was in the same spot in the kitchen.  However, the mysterious plant had disappeared.  Bob was surprised that he had returned to the present time. "I discovered the key to time travel and didn't even know it," Bob said to himself.  From that time on, Bob regularly enjoyed traveling through time now that he knew how to get back home.

3d6d562a736a49509c20be372a83d111.prefix:
Humans once wielded formidable magical power. But with over 7 billion of us on the planet now, Mana has spread far too thinly to have any effect. When hostile aliens reduce humanity to a mere fraction, the survivors discover an old power has begun to reawaken once again.

The story begins with a young man named Riku, who lives in a world where magic has long been forgotten. He has been raised in Landro by his grandfather Frezna, a wizard, and has always dreamed of becoming a great wizard himself.  Riku didn't know what had ever happened to his parents; his grandfather refused to tell him.  He lived a lonely, isolated life and longed for a family outside his grandfather.  There were no photographs of his parents; the only picture was of a woman.  Sometimes he would see his grandfather gazing at the photograph, a wistful look on his face.  

His grandfather spent years training him, but it takes a long, long time to learn everything one needs to know to use magic to its full extent.  When Riku was 14, his grandfather passed away.  Riku had been kept at home his whole life and knew little about the world, but now he had to set out and find his way.  He decided to go to the city of Faltra, where he had heard from his grandfather that there were many people who could teach him about magic.

Riku's first day in Faltra is a disaster.  They spoke a different dialect than he had learned growing up,
3d6d562a736a49509c20be372a83d111.infix: so it was very difficult to get around.  He did have a little money and was finally able to find a room to

constraints.suffix:
rent.  He knew he needed to find a job, and find someone to continue teaching him magic.  Over the next few weeks, he learned the dialect and started to find his way around the city.  He got a job at a bakery, where he worked hard and met a lot of people as he waited on them.  He made friends with a young girl named Selphie, who was a waitress at the bakery.  They became friends immediately, and it was almost like they had known one another forever.

One day, Selphie invited Riku to come to her house for dinner.  Selphie lived with her grandmother. He arrived with some flowers he had picked.  When he knocked on the door, an elderly woman opened it.  Riku stood in the doorway, frozen solid.  It was an older version of the woman in the photograph that his grandfather had.  Riku knew it had to be her; he too had spent hours looking at that photograph.  The woman also stood very still, staring at him.

"Riku," she said.  "Is it you?"

"Have we met?" Riku asked?

"Have you come here from Landro?"

"Yes," Riku said.

"Is Frezna your grandfather,"

"Yes," Riku responded.

"Where is he?"

"He died, and I came to Faltra to find someone to continue my magic education."

The woman motioned him inside, and sat heavily on the sofa, tears running down her face.  She told Riku she was his grandmother, and when his parent were killed by magic hunters, she and her husband had each taken one of the children and fled to keep them safe and keep teaching them magic.  Selphie was his sister!  By this point, she had joined them in the parlor and they both listed to the story their grandmother told.  She was teaching Selphie magic, but neither Riku nor Selphie's magic would be strong until they were reunited, as they were twins.  She hadn't known that her husband had passed away.  They hadn't seen each other in nearly 12 years, but had kept in touch as best they could.  

Riku and Selphie were overjoyed to be reunited, and they spent the evening talking and catching up. Riku and Selphie spent the next year honing their magic and making plans for how to use their powers to return Mana to its past glory.  That would be their next adventure.

85592766aa1940778f8f71cda90305e1.prefix:
Humans once wielded formidable magical power. But with over 7 billion of us on the planet now, Mana has spread far too thinly to have any effect. When hostile aliens reduce humanity to a mere fraction, the survivors discover an old power has begun to reawaken once again. 

This is the story of the rebirth of magic in a world where it has long been forgotten.  

The story is told through the eyes of the main character, a young man named Riku. He is the son of a powerful mage, and has been trained in the art of magic from a young age. He is the only one of his kind to have been born in a hundred years. 

The story begins when Riku is a young boy, and follows him as he grows up and learns to control his magic.
85592766aa1940778f8f71cda90305e1.infix: He is sent to a school for mages, where he meets many other students his age. Very similar to Harry Potter and Hogwarts.

constraints.suffix:
Riku is a very quick learner and is the top of his class. 

His ability to learn magic is uncanny. He is able to learn spells that take others years to master in a matter of days. He is also able to cast spells that no one else can. He is a very powerful mage and has the potential to be the best mage of all time. 

Riku is also very skilled in the art of hand to hand combat. He is able to take on many enemies at once and defeat them with ease. Nobody can touch him. Except for one other student. Koru is the only other student who is learning the art of magic at the speed Riku is. However Koru is using magic to do harm. 

He is a very evil person and is the complete opposite of Riku. He is able to cast spells that Riku has never seen before. The two go into battle. Riku wants to save the world. Koru wants to take over the world. 

The story continues as Riku grows up and is forced to make decisions that will change the world forever. Koru gives Riku an ultimatum. Koru will go away forever but the only way to eliminate him is to eradicate 10 countries. Riku doesn't want to cause any harm. Koru won't budge on his ultimatum.

Riku comes up with a plan to trick Koru. He casts a fake spell that is supposed to eliminate 10 countries in the world. He then casts a spell that turns Koru into a plant before he can even realize that Riku didn't actually eliminate the 10 planets. Koru lives the rest of his life as a plant. Riku lives the rest of his life practicing magic and leaving a positive impact on everyone he comes into contact with.

Riku was able to defeat his arch rival and also save the world. A beautiful first chapter to this series. However in the next book a more powerful and more evil force will challenge Riku. Will Riku be up to the challenge or will evil triumph over good? For the sake of humanity lets hope good beats evil just like the cliche says.

Humans once wielded formidable magical power. But with over 7 billion of us on the planet now, Mana has spread far too thinly to have any effect. When hostile aliens reduce humanity to a mere fraction, the survivors discover an old power has begun to reawaken once again.

This power now seems to be the key to mankind's survival, and perhaps the only weapon we have left to combat the hostile aliens. In a generation, the power of mana has condensed greatly and many powerful mages or mana users have emerged. Some with natural talent, some who excelled with training, and both. 

Among those who have mastered the use of mana are dizygotic twins named Jenn and Jonn. The twins both are 'Mana Blessed' with extraordinary power among all mana users, those dubbed this have the highest degree of natural talent with mana. The twins are able to cast spells and wield otherwise primitive weapons infused with mana. This is common for mana users in general but ramped up extremely with training and natural talent. 

Strangely, the twins are able to cast spells tath are extremely powerful seemingly without actively thinking about it. The spells arise in many cases automatically. Both the twins have been unconsciously saved by these high-level spells, as in the
81f59f9cba194b04802bbeae51dc798c.infix:
case when Jenn was saved from drowning by one such spell. 

Given their level of

constraints.suffix:
mana attunement, the twins quickly rose up the ranks of the remaining humans. These ranks are based on mana power, which has quickly become the most important attribute in human society. 

After the aliens attacked and nearly destroyed all of humanity, the small group of human survivors lived in secret locations scattered in dense remote regions in the world, away from the alien colonies which remained on the planet. The twins became the leaders of one particular location, and rumors spread to the other secret locations of the power of these "Mana Blessed" twins. 

Jenn and Jonn consolidated the most powerful mana users from all the human bastions. They led the humans in a rebellion against the alien colonies. The aliens and their high technology were overwhelmed by the sheer power of this new generation of mana users. The aliens were driven back to their original, more fortified colonies. The human resistance was faced with a greater technological threat in these locations, which contained motherships and armies of drones ships. 

The most critical battle was fought in the Atlantica region, which was the largest hub of alien colonization. Jonn fell in the battle, sacrificing himself with a powerful spell to wipe out the most powerful motherships on the planet. Jenn remained to lead the humans to exterminate the remaining aliens, and lead humanity to rebuild and flourish as they once did.

d4a9f1685bf541d29e96abe560ef4589.prefix: Humans once wielded formidable magical power. But with over 7 billion of us on the planet now, Mana has spread far too thinly
d4a9f1685bf541d29e96abe560ef4589.infix: to have any effect. When hostile aliens reduce humanity

constraints.suffix:
to a mere fraction, the survivors discover an old power has begun to reawaken once again.

Today is the culmination of all of our hard work; the energy from the Mana would be focused into a vessel, granting them extraordinary power. The ceremony was taking place in the center of the city, in a large open area. Large, needlelike stones stood around the ring, focusing the Mana's flow.   The energy would be focused into a single person, who would become the savior of humanity. 

I watched in awe as more and more people showed up for the choosing ceremony. 
The Mana was flowing through the city, and the needle-like stones were glowing brightly. On an Altar in the middle of the room, 
the energy wisped into a curling ball of rolling light. It was beautiful. 

The light seemed to be taking a form, and I could see a shape in the center of the light. It was a man, with a long, flowing cloak. But it faded away, and was replaced by another. This one was a woman, with long, flowing hair.  Several other forms appeared and then vanished inside the swirling light. 

The light faded away, and the crowd began to murmur. I turned to see The high priest Diovar from the far-away city of Capernus, and his purple hooded acolytes make their way to the middle of the ring. The High Priest raised his arms, and the crowd fell silent. "The time has come," he said. "The Mana has chosen its vessel." 
"The Mana has chosen..."


Suddenly, without warning, laser fire broke out. The trees nearby were flattened, as the cloaked alien cruisers lowered to the ground. 
The crowd began to panic. The Aliens had arrived. 
The aliens were tall, with long, gangly limbs. With their natural strength, they leaped from the ship,  ripping apart the innocent citizens with their bare hands.   

I noticed a charge land on the Altar. "The Mana" I yelled. I saw the altar be blown apart, in millions of pieces, the light went out from the mana globe. There was a loud ringing noise, and then everything went black.

I agree to help and go to a specified location. Upon arriving I am sat in front of a desk and given a little dial which can be turned left or right. 

A mysterious man in a suit enters the room. He hands me a folder with the words "You're our last hope" on the cover.

I read it and it says that half of the people in our world are from another reality. It's part of what is called the Mandella effect. This is for me to decide as part of the JFK project. 

If I turn the dial all the way to the right all of the people from that reality disappear. If I turn it to the left all the people from the other reality do. The man leaves the room and I am left to decide this for myself. 

What if I am wrong? We'll be a world filled with only people from another reality. Am I from another reality? Will I disappear as well?

I don't want to do it but I am familiar with the JFK project. I have to do it. I close my eyes, hoping I don't disappear and turn the dial to the left. Now there is only darkness and nothing more.

The next day, you receive your first letter. It reads:

I want you to start by doing something that I never did. I want you to go to a gun store and buy a gun. Then, I want you to go to a shooting range and learn how to use it. Then call me back.

JFK

You're Barack Obama. 4 years into your retirement, you awake to find a letter with no return address on your bedside table. It reads "I hope you've had a chance to relax Barack...but pack your bags and call the number below. It's time to start the real job." Signed simply, "JFK."

JFK has always been a bit of a prankster with you, so you're not sure if this is a joke or not. You decide to text JFK to make sure he's not just pulling your leg. 

JFK doesn't respond to your text, which is unusual because he's always been a quick texter. In fact, you've never known him to not respond to a text. You decide to call him instead. 

JFK picks up on the first ring. "Hey Barack, what's up?" he asks. 

"I got this letter from you and I was just calling to
25ad6925dd65422989e3659250ac9bfd.infix:
make sure it wasn't a joke."

JFK has no idea what you're talking about, and he's a little offended that you'd think he'd pull a prank like that. "I didn't send

constraints.suffix:
you a letter, Barack." 

"Well, I have it right here on my bedside table." JFK asks you to read it aloud to him. 

"Well, it says 'I hope you've had a chance to relax Barack...but pack your bags and call the number below." 

JFK is a little creeped out that someone would be impersonating him. "Well, why don't you call the number and see what happens?"

You decide to do a three-way call so that JFK can hear the conversation. 

The phone rings once, twice, three times...and then a voice answers. As it turns out, the voice belongs to none other than John F. Kennedy. You're confused, because JFK just told you that he had no idea who sent you that letter and swore to you that it wasn't him. You ask JFK what's going on, since he is also on the line as a looped-in call participant. 

JFK is just as confused as you are. But make no mistake, this is definitely JFK on the other end of the line -- in fact, it is definitely JFK on both ends of the line for the three-way call.

You have no idea what to think of the situation. You ask JFK to explain the contents of the letter and the man who answered your call responds, "It's a job offer to come be my personal chef." 

"But I'm retired," you say. "Plus, I don't know how to cook. You know that, ever since I tried hosting that dinner party the one time and everyone got food poisoning."

The man who answered your call has no idea what you're talking about, even though JFK was certainly a guest at the dinner party you are referencing and most certainly must remember the horrible food poisoning he got from eating your attempt at roasted chicken with a side of mashed potatoes.

Suddenly, you realize what must be going on. You must be living in parallel time zones or parallel worlds, because JFK is in one world and the man who answered your call is in another, even though both of these men are JFK. The theory is a little wonky but quite frankly, you're not sure what else to think. There is no other good explanation for these circumstances. The man who answered your call must have offered you the job as a chef because he doesn't realize, as the real JFK should realize, how bad your cooking skills are. 

You feel a little weird that you must have your feet straddling two different time periods, but you decide to go with it. I mean, you've seen weirder things while living in the White House. You bid the two JFKs goodbye on the phone after explaining your theory of what's going on, and the two JFKs are surprised as well. Interestingly, that aspect of your life is the only one that you experience this split time zone experience over!

Matt Damon is terrified and confused, but the alien quickly explains that he is merely a huge fan, and just wants an autograph.   

Matt Damon is not convinced, and the alien is forced to take Matt Damon to his home planet to prove that he is actually an alien, and not a crazed kidnapper who has built a hovercraft and disguised it as a spaceship.

The alien is nonplussed, but agrees to travel across the universe with his favorite actor.

Matt Damon, being a celebrity, quickly forgets all about the famine and the invaders, and ends up basking in the admiration of yet another adoring fan.  

In fact, Matt thinks, he could make a fortune if the studios recognize all of the revenue that his movies are earning outside of Earth, so he asks for a tour of the planet, where he can meet more fans.

The alien shows Matt Damon around, and a few of the locals are thrilled to see him, but most of them just ignore him.  It turns out, that Matt Damon only has a few fans outside of the solar system, and only one of them has even watched his movies.  

Matt is disappointed, but he at least figures that he could get inspiration for a new movie from what he sees, so he asks to go to the library to learn more about the invaders.

The alien takes Matt Damon to the library, and Matt Damon is shocked to see that the library is a tiny, one-room building with a single display screen in it.

On that screen, Matt instantly watches the entire history of this planet, and all of his questions are answered.  

He asks to return to Earth, and even invites the alien to stay with him in Los Angeles.

The alien, however, refuses.

As much as he loves Matt Damon, the alien admits, he would rather live in a barren wasteland where his life is in constant danger, than have to live on the same planet as Ben Affleck


THE END

For John, he had a fairly uneventful life. He had a fulfliling job, a stable family, and he had plenty of money and time to pursue his hobbies and interests. It would appear that nothing too major would affect him in his life, but that was not the case. For John experienced the oddest event one day, one that would bring about adversity in his life.

His children had gifted him a mug last Father's day, which he cherished and used every day for his morning tea. He liked to drink it to relax before work, and his children were happy whenever they saw him use the mug they bought for him. However, one day they woke up and looked at him funny while he was drinking his tea.

"You get a new mug Dad?" asked his daughter, who was at the time only four years old. Puzzled, John replied no. For it was the same mug he drank from every day since last Father's day, a step-up from the plain ceramic mug he used to drink tea from.

Turning the mug around, he noted that his children were indeed correct, the mug he held did not say #1 Dad. In fact it said, #54 Dad. Thinking it was an elaborate prank from his family, John asked his children where his old mug was. They all shrugged their shoulders and said they didn't know. Asking his wife who was heading to work, she seemed as confused as he was regarding the mug, and denied any involvement in the different appearance of the mug.

In any case, John placed the mug in the sink, and would come back to clean it later. He

constraints.suffix:
at school, and returned back home to get to work. Work went on as normal, but when he went to get his mug from the sink he noticed something bizarre. The mug he placed in the sink now said #50 Dad. It dropped down by 4 numbers, he was sure of it. Growing more confused, he thought someone had broken into his house, but he had found no signs of forced entry, and his mug was in the same place he had set it down. Grabbing the mug, he took a picture of it, and made a post online about how odd it was for his mug to say such a thing. Most applauded him for buying such a novel mug, and did not give his incident any further thought.

However, the next day the mug would now say #65 Dad. Like before, John posted the same picture, and people were again amused by the novelty of such a mug. Some even mentioning he had dropped several ranks down, and asked what he did to become worse than he was before.

The following days would be the same type of incidents. He would post the mug with his new rank, which sometimes did not change at all and on other days were fairly different than the day before. He become well known as the man with the changing mug, and people were genuinely interested in the mug, and the reason for it's weirdness. Others were skeptical, and claimed John had multiple mugs made, but his friends and family all supported John, and noted he had quite few mugs stored in his house, with most of them being blank. For the remainder of his life, John had become well known to others not for his notoriety or prestige from his actions or efforts, nor from his job and or position in life. He was known for his novel ceramic mug, which reflected his rank in the world, and showed others that indeed someone or some force was ranking all the dads in the world, and maybe there was a way to measure how good a father a person can really be.

joke. As he was about to head to the shower he noticed that his other mug that his wife bought him shortly after their daughter was born said "#5467 Dad". He was dumbfounded. "They really went all in on this prank" Jeff thought to himself as he jumped in the shower.

As he drove to work, he noticed a lot of people out and about in his neighborhood yelling at each other in various stages of dress. As he pulled into the parking lot of his office building he noticed that all of the cars had their windows down and coffee mugs out. Everyone was comparing how "Dadly" they were. Phil from accounting was strutting around with a mug that ranked him as the 433rd best dad, but Mark the new guy in the mailroom showed him his "#102 Dad" mug. Phil threw his mug in the trash. He entered the office and as he walked down the hall, he noticed that all of the doors were open and people where shouting about who was the better dad. Then all of the sudden Sally from the warehouse came screaming down the hall saying they found the real "#1 Dad" in Rome, it ended up being the Pope.  Everyone was stunned to see the Pope was a dad. 

After a few weeks people settled into their roles as not number one Dad, but tried everyday to make the number on the side of their mugs go up. Due to economic instability and other factors plaguing the countries of the world, an agreement was made for each country to go into isolation, for the next 100 years. This means that the countries will not be able to travel outside of their borders, nor communicate with other nations. This was approved by many if not most of the nations of the world, and was backed up by countless experts who agreed that isolation was needed for the world to stabilize itself. With the approval of the world's leaders, the countries of the world entered isolation on the year 2101, remaining isolated from others until the year 2102.

Within the first year, all forms of communication were cut off, and the only way to communicate was through a network of satellites set up across nations in case of a severe emergency, that required the intervention of other countries to aid one another. However, the satellites were never utilized in the hundred of years of isolation. In fact, it appeared as if most countries were fine during isolation, able to recover economically and become stable as experts had predicted. There were no wars or conflicts, and the world continued to move on without major issues that would
23b998c76c784ff29f0ddedd78128722.infix: involve many nations around a singular issue. In fact, the

constraints.suffix:
only thing that seemed to really be a problem was that international trade was basically nonexistent. As per the rules of isolation, many countries were prohibited from trading with other countries goods and services. This proved problematic for some countries, but the lack of communication via satellites during the duration of the satellites suggested that those countries would find domestic means to satisfy their resource needs.

The year 2112 eventually arrived, and communications between countries were re-established. However, it was soon discovered that there were major issues that had arisen in the absence of communication and trade throughout the world. Many of the third-world countries had been able to make due during the isolation, but the first-world countries had suffered from the lack of trade, in addition to other economic issues. These countries for whatever reason it may be did not chose to use the satellite communication during the period of isolation, out of pride and fear that the other countries would view them as vulnerable. This was proven to be a fatal mistake, as these countries were not prepared for the monumental challenges that they faced in the return of communication. Many of the countries that suffered from isolation ended up going into conflicts with one another, for resources and other material goods that it had lacked during the isolation. Trade battles and other economic struggles occurred between the biggest nations of the world, dragging the smaller countries into it causing them to suffer as well. It turns out that isolation was not the answer to the world's problems, and that the only way for nations to survive was continue to communicate and work with one another. During the period of isolation, no problems, no wars or conflicts, and no apparent struggles were reported around the world. For those problems were building up and lying in wait, waiting for the end of isolation. In the return to communication, those problems all came rushing out, being much more severe than if the nations never had isolated in the first place.

She did not want to scare me as a child, so she never told me that my allergy could be fatal, but as I got older I learned otherwise. I stayed in doors as much as I could in my first two years of college, quickly running from building to building in order to avoid any bees. I always wore long sleeves and pants, even in the summer, in order to avoid any stings. My friends never questioned my actions and accepted me for who I was. The bee told me that I did not have a deadly allergy, and that my mother had lied to me. I wondered why my mother would lie to me about something so strange. When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the “Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

I thought that there was a lot of hubub on the news, but I didn't know what it was all about until I sat down to really pay attention. "It's a tragedy!" the newscaster was gasping. "The government has been hiding the side effects of the immortality drug for decades!" I settled into my seat, feeling my knees creak and hearing my joints audibly pop. I winced. I'd always half felt sorry for myself that I was too old for
bc89dc4ac2a04f3aae685f619bb0fd24.infix: the drug, but the other half of me knew, just knew that the other shoe would drop some day. I

constraints.suffix:
sighed and adjusted my pillow behind my aching back as I turned up the volume to listen. My ear weren't what they used to be.

"They're pulling the drug immediately!" the newscaster was almost shrieking, and I could see her panic. "They say the effects of the drug will wear off exactly 58 years after they were first administeded!" I could see the shock and disbelief of her terrifically youthful face. "We're all going to get...old!" She could barely get the word out. Like it was a curse. I felt a twinge of pity for her. Here I'd had my whole like to settle into myself and get used to the aches and pains, to get comfortable with the notion of my own mortality. These younger people who had lived their whole lives feeling immortal They were about to hit a hard reality.

I turned off the TV and settled back into my chair. This would change everything, I realized. There would be repercussions all through society. People who had put off having kids because they had all the time in the world suddenly had no time. There weren't many kids around, I realized. The world could be in for a whole lot of trouble if its whole work force suddenly aged out of their ablilty to work. My dawning sense of dread was only slightly assuaged by the fact that I was too old to really feel the repercussions of this. I'd be dead before it really got bad. I pressed the button on my phone to call the assistant in my home. I loved it here, I mused, as I waited for her to respond. This retirement community was the perfect place to hide out and live my last decade or two in peace. I pushed the button again. And again. Finally I called the front desk. A harried voice answered. 

"Is it an emergency?" the woman squawked at me, "You should call the police if it is. Nobody's coming! Everyone left!" I sat up. "What did you say?" The dread was spreading through me like a nagging fever in my bones. "They left!" She repeated. "They all realized they don't have much time left to be young; nobody wanted to be stuck here for the last good year they have left!"

"But you're still here," I tried to argue, although I heard the wavering in my own voice. 

"I'll be outta here as soon as I find my purse," she said distractedly. "Sorry, pal. You're on your own."

And then I realized that everything was about to change for the worse, and not just for the fools who tried to make themselves young forever.   I was about to be alone. For the rest of my life. However long it would be.

By then, the world is almost entirely filled with bright-eyed, attractive, youthful young adults. People like you have to hide on the edges of society, avoiding their judgemental gazes at all costs as you become more and more decrepit and they remain strikingly beautiful.

Because of that, you don't even hear about the breakthrough discovery until weeks after it's become a global sensation. The first time you hear about it, you're in the middle of a crowd of young adults waiting to get into the grocery store.

A girl in front of you in the line spots you and grabs you by the shoulders.

you off your feet with her youthful strength. "You're one of the Lost Generations, aren't you?"

It's silly that she needs to ask, because

constraints.suffix:
it's obvious. But you nod anyways.

Her tears fall faster. "Please remember me," she sobs, flinging herself into your arms and squeezing your shoulders in a tight embrace. "Remember all of us when we... when we..."

Her words choke to a halt, leaving you baffled and afraid.

A young man approaches you and places his hand on her back. He also looks sad.

"We're sorry," he says to you. "For all the times people like us... well. We didn't know, of course. And we never got the choice, did we? People like us... this is the end of the line, isn't it?"

You don't know what to say. You have no idea what they're talking about. So you nod, hoping it might mean something to them.

Sniffling, the girl detaches from you and takes the young man's hand. "Please remember us," she repeats, giving you one last mournful stare before stepping through the store door.

As the automated door shuts behind her, you realize it's covered in a large poster, marked with the seal of the government. It's a warning about the side effects of the immortality drug.

You read the poster, and the world falls out from under you.

"Due to the violent development of suicidal-homocidal tendencies in adults who have received anti-ageing treatment, we ask that all members of the affected population (ages 26-83) turn themselves in for containment and voluntary destruction. This facility has been marked as a designated internment location. Groceries for youths and members of the Lost Generations can be found down the road at the convention center."

e192ae618004434e80f6d9ac86b84b05.prefix:
When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the side effects are finally discovered.

Dan woke up early that morning, as usual, had his cup of coffee, like usual, and sat down to watch the morning news, as usual. Everything was as it always was. To be honest, he was beginning to
e192ae618004434e80f6d9ac86b84b05.infix: be okay with the fact that he

constraints.suffix:
would die someday - it wasn't the bitter disappointment is was almost 60 years ago. 

But then the morning was "as usual" anymore. 

Dan was watching the news when the anchorwoman, a young woman who had been with the station for about a year, suddenly froze. She looked about 22, the age most people got the drug, though some got it as early as 16. She was frozen in place, her eyes wide and her mouth slightly open. Staring at the paper and then the teleprompter in front of her. She finally spoke, voice shaky, "I'm sorry, we have breaking news." Last month the earliest recipients of the drug 4EvR all reported to medical centers complaining of headaches. Within 6 hours they had lost their vision and hearing. Within 24 hours they seemed to be comatose, though brain scans showed the same activity levels as a normal, conscious person. They remain in that state."

Dan stared at the screen in shock. The newscaster continued. "Scientists have been studying their condition and have come to the conclusion that it is due to the drug 4EvR." She began to cry, "And according to their findings it is not only an inevitable side effect, but also one that is triggered or transmitted to users. To summarize, all people who have ever taken 4EvR will almost certainly have been exposed to others who have been exposed to the original group and we should all expect to experience the same side effects within 2 weeks at the most." 

Dan turned off the TV. He was in shock. He had never taken the drug missing the age cut off by a mere two years, but all of his younger relatives had. His children, his grandchildren, so many others. Ans soon they would essentially be helpless with only a few aged people like himself to take care of them. 

Dan was suddenly filled with rage. It wasn't fair. He had had expectations, and now everything was upside down. This was not his problem to deal with. He sat at his desk, and shaking, wrote notes to all his loved ones. He wrote a note to his children, telling them how much he loved them, and how he was sorry that he couldn't be there to help them. And then he went upstairs, and found the bottle of pills, the same ones his wife had used a few years ago when she just got tired of being old in a young world. And he took many more than needed. And left the world before everyone, just like he always thought he would.
